Discrete event Systems simulation - Le√≥n XIII Clinic - Emergency department

Daniel

21/2/2020

This project aims to fit distributions to the services inside the emergency department of the Le√≥n XIII clinic, located in Medell√≠n - Colombia using real data from the users and their arrivals. Extensive use of the fitdistrplus package is made in the development of this methodology.

After the distributions are fitted, discrete event simulation will be performed using Simul8 to stablish performance measures and prescriptive analytics that could improve the decision making process.

1 Libraries

library(tidyverse)
library(fitdistrplus)
library(lubridate)

Admision office dynamics could be hidden inside the data repetition, need to assessment including the triages.

These two datasets are joined because in the first extraction of raw_data, the triage type information was not on the SQL query, therefore a later query called datos_complementarios was made, that was bigger than the original raw_data and included the triage information. The original data remained unaltered and the triage information was joined to it.

3 Creation of the duration of events

clean_data <- raw_data %>%
  distinct(salida_taquilla, .keep_all = TRUE)

tiempo_llegadas <- diff(sort(clean_data$salida_taquilla))

tiempos <- clean_data %>% 
  mutate(cola_triage = entrada_triage - salida_taquilla,
         dur_triage = fin_triage - entrada_triage,
         cola_servicio = entrada_servicio - fin_triage,
         dur_servicio = salida_servicio - entrada_servicio) %>%
  mutate_at(vars(cola_triage, dur_triage, cola_servicio, dur_servicio), as.numeric) %>% 
  dplyr::select(atencion, servicio, servicio_detalle, cola_triage, 
                dur_triage, cola_servicio, dur_servicio) %>%
  filter_if(is.numeric, all_vars(. > 10)) %>% # Validado con asistenciales
  filter(cola_triage <= 14400, # Hasta 4 horas, validado con doctores de urgencias 
         cola_servicio <= 43200) # Hasta 24 horas, validado con asistenciales

3.1.1 Considerations

  • All the durations considered will last at least 30 seconds.
  • Triage queues higher than 12 hours will be discarded, the same goes for service time queues higher than 36 hours.

6 Distribution selection

cullen_fray <- map(tiempos[,c(5,7)], descdist, discrete = FALSE, boot = 1000)

cullen_fray_llegadas <- descdist(as.numeric(tiempo_llegadas), boot = 1000)

Distributions will only be fitted to the duration of the services, as the queues are of no interest, but rather an output of the discrete event simulation.

7 Distribution fitting

7.1 Triage duration

Exponential distribution, gamma distribution and lognormal distribution are good candiadates for the data based on the kurtosis (10.7491014) and skewness (2.2209812) of the data.

7.1.1 Exponential distribution

fit_triage_exp <- fitdist(tiempos$dur_triage, distr = "exp", method = "mle")
fit_triage_exp
## Fitting of the distribution ' exp ' by maximum likelihood 
## Parameters:
##       estimate   Std. Error
## rate 0.0035587 6.057445e-05
plot(fit_triage_exp)

Null hyphotesis rejected based on the Q-Q plot, the data can‚Äôt possibly be represented by an exponential distribution.

7.1.2 Gamma distribution

fit_triage_gamma <- fitdist(tiempos$dur_triage, distr = "gamma", method = "mle")
fit_triage_gamma
## Fitting of the distribution ' gamma ' by maximum likelihood 
## Parameters:
##          estimate  Std. Error
## shape 2.532456026 0.060685143
## rate  0.009012918 0.000235833
plot(fit_triage_gamma)

Null hyphotesis could be rejected, need further testing.

7.1.3 Lognormal

fit_triage_lognormal <- fitdist(tiempos$dur_triage, distr = "lnorm", method = "mle")
fit_triage_lognormal
## Fitting of the distribution ' lnorm ' by maximum likelihood 
## Parameters:
##          estimate  Std. Error
## meanlog 5.4281722 0.012517019
## sdlog   0.6708001 0.008850781
plot(fit_triage_lognormal)

Data is definitely lognormal, need to conduct formal hypothesis testing here.

7.2 Service duration

The services are individual, so an aggregation of these doesn‚Äôt seem appropiate at all. The individual services are:

servicio n
Urgencias 2223
Urgencias Pediatria 575
Hospitalizacion Adultos 34
Quirurgicos 21
UCI Adultos 11
CUIDADOS ESPECIALES 8

A general try anyway:

Gamma distribution and lognormal distribution could be good candiadates for the data based on the kurtosis (38.7056184) and skewness (4.8010565) of the data using Cullen and Frey‚Äôs graphical method.

7.2.1 Gamma distribution

Need an scaling factor for the gamma to work, need to reference this.

fit_servicio_gamma <- fitdist(tiempos$dur_servicio/250, distr = "gamma", method = "mle")
fit_servicio_gamma
## Fitting of the distribution ' gamma ' by maximum likelihood 
## Parameters:
##          estimate   Std. Error
## shape 0.760136694 1.391795e-02
## rate  0.002171234 3.666788e-05
plot(fit_servicio_gamma)

Gamma distribution doesn‚Äôt seem to work very well with this data. May need more tunning.

7.2.2 Lognormal distribution

fit_servicio_lognormal <- fitdist(tiempos$dur_servicio, distr = "lnorm", method = "mle")
fit_servicio_lognormal
## Fitting of the distribution ' lnorm ' by maximum likelihood 
## Parameters:
##          estimate Std. Error
## meanlog 10.593692 0.02272588
## sdlog    1.217904 0.01606957
plot(fit_servicio_lognormal)

Lognormal distribution may work, need further verification. Theorically there is no distribution that can fit these data, as there are distinguishable categories that behave differently inside the data. Separation by service is needed.
